        'source_url' => 'https://www.thepoortraveler.net/laiya-batangas-resorts/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Poor Traveler',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Laiya San Juan Beach Guide: A Slow Batangas Weekend',
        'slug' => 'laiya-san-juan-beach-guide-slow-weekend',
        'excerpt' => 'Laiya in San Juan, Batangas is the calmer alternative to Boracay when you only have a weekend. Shallow water, child-friendly waves, and a three-hour ride from Manila.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Laiya is the Batangas beach Manila settles on when the airport feels like too much work. The water is clear, the waves are gentle, and the strip of sand in Barangay Hugom is long enough that even on holiday weekends you can find a quiet stretch to set up. The trip works as a two-day, one-night weekender or as a slow three-day reset.</p><p>The name Laiya covers three barangays, Laiya Ibabao, Laiya Aplaya, and Hugom, but most visitors mean the public beach in Hugom. That is the one with the small islands offshore that break the waves before they reach the sand.</p><h2>How to Get There</h2><p>From Manila, take a bus bound for San Juan, Batangas from Cubao, Buendia, PITX, BGC, or Alabang. <a href="https://www.jamliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">JAM Liner</a> and <a href="https://dltbco.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">DLTBCo</a> both run regular trips. Fare runs around PHP 250 to 320, travel time three to four hours. From the San Juan town terminal, ride a tricycle or jeepney for around 30 minutes to Hugom.</p><h3>If You Are Driving</h3><p>Take SLEX, STAR Tollway, and exit Lipa. From Lipa, follow signs through Rosario into San Juan. The last 20 kilometers cut through coconut farms and small barangays. Drive slow, dogs and tricycles share the road.</p><h2>The Beach</h2><p>The Hugom strip has fine white sand and shallow water. The small islands offshore, Hugom Island and Sombrero, knock down the swells before they reach the shore, which is why families with kids favor Laiya over the more open Calatagan beaches. Snorkeling near the islands is doable but the reef is patchy.</p><h3>What the Day Looks Like</h3><p>Wake up early for sunrise on the beach. By 8 a.m. you can rent a kayak or paddleboard. Mid-morning, walk the strip toward the public beach and back. Lunch is grilled fish from the small carinderias or a wet-market run for fresh seafood you cook at the resort. Nap through the heat, then swim again at golden hour.</p><h3>Island Hopping</h3><p>Boats from the Hugom shore run short island-hopping trips to Sombrero Island, Hugom Island, and the small unnamed sandbars in between. The loop takes around three hours and the boatmen will pack lunch if you arrange ahead.</p><h2>What to Pack</h2><ul><li>Rashguard, the sun reflects off the white sand</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen with zinc oxide</li><li>A dry bag for your phone, the kayak rides get splashy</li><li>Small bills for cottage rentals and tricycle fares</li><li>A reusable water bottle, plastic bottles end up in the sea</li></ul><h2>Where to Stay</h2><p>Hugom has a mix of public beach cottages and private beach resorts along the strip. The smarter play is to base in a resort with direct beach access so you can roll out of bed to the sand. For listings across the Laiya coast, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g6817345-San_Juan_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Stay closer to Hugom proper if you want the shorter walk to the public stretch.</p><h2>Quick Tips Before You Go</h2><ul><li>Book ahead during summer, the strip fills up fast on weekends</li><li>Bring cash, ATMs in San Juan town are not reliable</li><li>Tip the cottage attendants, they help with the sand setup</li><li>Skip plastic straws, the local barangay is strict on waste</li></ul><p>Laiya is the kwento you tell when someone asks where to take their family for a calm weekend. Three hours from Manila, clear water, and the kids can swim without you watching every wave. That alone makes it worth the trip.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.thepoortraveler.net/laiya-batangas-resorts/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">The Poor Traveler</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Laiya San Juan Batangas Beach Weekend Guide | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'Plan a calm Laiya weekend in San Juan, Batangas. Shallow water, child-friendly waves, a three-hour ride from Manila, and a slow two-day route.',
        'tags' => 'Laiya, San Juan, Batangas, beach, weekend, family',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'laiya',
