        'source_url' => 'https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2017/04/fortune-island-batangas-guide/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Poor Traveler',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Fortune Island Nasugbu: A Greek Ruins Day Trip from Manila',
        'slug' => 'fortune-island-nasugbu-day-trip-from-manila',
        'excerpt' => 'Fortune Island in Nasugbu, Batangas has Greek-style ruins, a small white-sand cove, and a shipwreck snorkel. Here is the calm day-trip plan from Manila.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Fortune Island is the 27-hectare island off Nasugbu, Batangas with the Greek-style columns that flooded Instagram in the late 2010s. The luxury resort that built it shut down in 2006, and the ruins now stand on a cliff above the West Philippine Sea with no real maintenance. That is part of the charm and part of the warning.</p><p>The trip works best as a day tour from Manila if you start early, or as an overnight if you want to catch sunrise on the cliff before the boats arrive.</p><h2>Getting to Nasugbu</h2><p>From EDSA-Taft, San Agustin Bus Line and <a href="https://dltbco.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">DLTBCo</a> run trips to Nasugbu. Fare runs PHP 200 to 300, travel time three to four hours. Get off at Nasugbu town center near Jollibee, then ride a tricycle to Barangay Wawa where the boats leave.</p><h3>Driving Route</h3><p>Take Cavitex to Kawit, then Aguinaldo Highway through Tagaytay and down to Nasugbu via the zig-zag road. Drive is around two and a half to three hours from Manila without traffic. Park at the Wawa boat terminal.</p><h2>The Boat Ride</h2><p>A whole-day outrigger boat that fits six to eight people runs around PHP 3,500. Per-person rates work out lower if you can fill the boat. The crossing from Wawa to Fortune Island takes around 45 minutes to one hour depending on the wind. If the boatmen tell you to leave by 2 p.m., listen, the channel chops up in the afternoon.</p><h2>What to See on the Island</h2><p>The Greek-style ruins sit at the high point of the island. The columns are weathered concrete, not marble, and they were built as part of the old resort\'s decorative grounds. The view from the cliff covers the open sea and on clear days, the outline of Lubang Island in Mindoro. Sunrise here is the better light.</p><h3>The Cove and the Shipwreck</h3><p>Below the ruins, a small white-sand cove fronts shallow turquoise water. The sand is fine, the water clear, and the snorkeling around the eastern point reaches a small sunken ship. The wreck is shallow, around five to seven meters deep, so even free-divers can reach it.</p><h2>What to Bring</h2><ul><li>Snorkel gear, rentals at the island are limited</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen with zinc oxide</li><li>A dry bag for your phone, the boat ride sprays</li><li>A wide-brim hat, the cliff has zero shade</li><li>Cash for the entrance fee and the boat rental</li><li>Drinking water and packed food, the island has minimal stalls</li><li>Garbage bag, carry everything back</li></ul><h2>Fees and Schedule</h2><p>Entrance fee for a day tour runs around PHP 300 per person. The boatmen often build a strong case for leaving by 2 p.m. because the afternoon wind picks up. Take it seriously. The crossing back into a headwind is no fun.</p><h2>Stay Overnight</h2><p>If you want to skip the rushed day trip, an overnight option lets you camp on the island under stars. The facilities are basic, bring your own tent and water. Sunrise on the cliff with no other tourists is the kwento that makes the trip.</p><p>For lodging on the mainland in Nasugbu if you want a comfortable base before the boat day, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729877-Nasugbu_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p><h2>Quick Tips</h2><ul><li>Negotiate the boat rate at Wawa, prices vary by season</li><li>Skip the Greek-pose photo at the cliff edge, the rocks are crumbling</li><li>Bring small bills for the entrance and tricycle</li><li>Wear closed water shoes, the trails on the island are sharp</li></ul><p>Fortune Island is one of those Batangas day trips that looks like a postcard once you climb the cliff. Move with the boatmen\'s schedule, respect the ruins, and you will leave with the photo and the kwento.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2017/04/fortune-island-batangas-guide/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">The Poor Traveler</a>.</em></p>',
